Here is the data that we have assembled in the previous 2 notebooks. We have 148 rows, or countries, since we removed a few that were actually just territories. As for columns, we have net trade status, which tells us if a country is a net importer or exporter of oil. Then, all the other columns show the value of one of seven variables in one of four years. GDP data, population data, land area data, and democracy index data all give basic information about a country, and have data for the years from 2020 to 2023. This is because we are using basic information about a country to predict the policy they will implement in the next year, so we need basic data that is one year older than the policy data. Finally, we have 3 columns of data on oil subsidy policy across 4 years: Price control data, subsidy data, and tax reduction data. These are all policies, and the data indicates what a country's policy position was in that category in a given year. We have data on these from 2021 to 2024. Finally, we also have columns for country and country code. This is redundant, so we will drop the column for country.

Now, let's do some initial analysis of these variables.

In[3]:
for column in ['Net Trade Status', 'Price Control in 2021',
       'Subsidy in 2021', 'Tax Reduction in 2021', 'Price Control in 2022',
       'Subsidy in 2022', 'Tax Reduction in 2022', 'Price Control in 2023',
       'Subsidy in 2023', 'Tax Reduction in 2023', 'Price Control in 2024',
       'Subsidy in 2024', 'Tax Reduction in 2024']:
    data[column].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Countries')
    plt.title('Distribution of ' + column)
    plt.show()

We will look at the subsidy data first. For each column, here is what each field means: Subsidy: 0 means no subsidies, 1 means some subsidy, 2 means there is "a recurring practice of freezing prices", and 3 means the situation is unclear. For most years, we can see that about half of countries have no subsidy, while the other countries are split about evenly between some subsidy and price freezing. A small number of them are unclear. With a practice of freezing prices included, these are qualitatively different from each other. Therefore, we will use pd.get_dummies to split them into separate columns. Tax reduction: 0 means fuel taxes were not reduced, 1 means they were, and 3 means unclear. This varies between years, but we can see a minority of countries have subsidies, and sometimes a tiny number are unclear. We will replace 3 with 0 in these columns so that unclear is marked as no reduction. With a small number of unclear values in the dataset, and most countries not reducing fuel taxes, this is the best way to make the data usable for the models we will be using. Price Control: this is 0 if prices are deregulated, and 1 if they are regulated. We can see that a majority of countries are regulated. With only 2 possible values, no pre-processing is necessary for this field. Finally, we can see that about a quarter of countries are net exporters of refined oil products, while the rest are net importers. As for the basic data on countries, we will make one change. We have data on the land area of each country, but we don't have a column for population density. Population density is a far more useful statistic, since it tells us more about what the conditions are in a country for people. which is more directly relevant for predicting policy decisions. Therefore, we will replace the column on land area with one on population density. After this change, we will do some analysis on those columns, and some bivariate analysis to see how columns relate to each other.

In[4]:
data.drop(['Country'], axis=1, inplace=True)

for year in range(2020,2024,1):
    density_field_name = 'population density in ' + str(year)
    population_field_name = 'population data in ' + str(year)
    area_field_name = 'land area data in ' + str(year)
    data[density_field_name] = data[population_field_name] / data[area_field_name]
    data.drop([area_field_name], axis=1, inplace=True)

Given the distribution of these variables, it makes sense to take the log of them to get a distribution that's closer to uniform. This will allow our models to better appreciate small differences in quantities on the left of these distributions.

In[6]:
for year in range(2020,2024,1):
    density_field_name = 'population density in ' + str(year)
    population_field_name = 'population data in ' + str(year)
    gdp_field_name = 'gdp data in ' + str(year)
    for field in [density_field_name, population_field_name, gdp_field_name]:
        data['log_' + field] = np.log10(data[field])
        data.drop([field], axis=1, inplace=True)

    display_name = column.replace('data ', '')
    display_name = display_name.replace('log_', 'log of ')
    plt.xlabel(display_name)
    display_name = display_name.replace('log of ', '')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Countries')
    if column[0:9] == 'democracy':
        plt.title('Distribution of ' + display_name)
    else:
        plt.title('Log distribution of ' + display_name)
    plt.show()

Those are far nicer distributions! Note that we took a log base 10, so a value of n means 1 followed by n zeros. Now, let's do a little bit of bivariate analysis to see what correlations can be inferred here.

From this, we can see a couple things. Correlations are mostly consistent across years. Countries with subsidies are more likely to directly regulate prices. This makes sense, since both tools are generally used to achieve similar goals. In addition, tax reductions and subsidies are negatively correlated. This may mean that tax reductions can be used as a substitute for direct subsidies.

For the next bivariate analysis, we will take only the latest year, as this will reveal all major trends without creating too many graphs.

    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Countries')
    plt.title('Distribution of ' + column)
    plt.show()

]We can notice a few correlations here as well. First, there is a large negative correlation between subsidies and a country's GDP. In other words, poor countries implement oil subsidies and price controls far more often than wealthy ones. Conversely, tax reductions are far more common in wealthy countries, suggesting that wealthy countries often use tax reductions similarly to how poor countries use subsidies. Wealthy countries are also far more likely to be net exporters of refined oil products. However, from this data alone, it is impossible to tell if exporting refined oil causes a country to get wealthy, having wealth causes a country to have refined oil to export, or if some other confounding variable is causing the correlation. Finally, we can see that the less democratic a country is, the higher the likelihood of that country regularly freezing prices.

# Manipulating categorical variables to make them quantitative
for year in range(2021,2025,1):
    tax_field_name = 'Tax Reduction in ' + str(year)
    subsidy_field_name = 'Subsidy in ' + str(year)
    data = pd.get_dummies(data, columns=[subsidy_field_name], dtype=int)
    print(data.head())
    # Naming columns based on the meaning of each value, and dropping the column corresponding to unclear. This value will be indicated by 0s in all other columns.
    data.drop(['Subsidy in ' + str(year) + '_3'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    data.rename(columns={'Subsidy in ' + str(year) + '_0':'No subsidy in ' + str(year), 'Subsidy in ' + str(year) + '_1':'Some subsidy in ' + str(year), 'Subsidy in ' + str(year) + '_2': 'Price freezes in ' + str(year)}, inplace=True)

    # Replacing the single unclear value so data fits into model nicely
    data[tax_field_name].replace(3, 0, inplace=True)
    print(data.head())
    print(data.columns)
